title: Three Point Printer Bed Frame for CTC Bizer (Replicator Clone) Makerbot Clone 3D Printers (FlashForge, Wanhao)

description.text:
Inspired by the model from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:673801 I designed this printbed frame for maximum stiffness and three point leveling. It's a solid design that I've been using since 2016 and am really satisfied with the results.

Scroll down to the video for assembly instructions.

Necessary materials are:

--> 2x 187mm long 15x15mm square aluminum profiles
--> 1x 128mm long 15x15mm square aluminum profile
--> 2x 275mm long 8mm O.D. aluminium tubes or rods. These should be installed at the same time as the long square aluminium profiles.
--> The aluminum plate is exactly 202.641x162.737mm. I had a 200x200mm buildplate from an i3 laying around that worked out just great for cutting out the plate. They can be had for little money and I don't mind the missing 2.641mm from the top flat edge. I have updloaded a PDF in A4 format to print on cardstock and use as a trace to cut out the aluminium plate. For those who want to go the extra mile there's also a DXF file for laser/water cutting.

--> If necessary one M8x15mm allen grub screw or bolt for the z-axis minimum switch.

A few M3 screws:
--> 8x 20mm for the frame
--> As many 6mm screws you want to use to mount the aluminum plate to the frame (6 should suffice). Bore holes at the corners, cut threads and screw it down!

Reuse the bronze nut for the z-axis leadscrew.

You will need to sand the holes for the bearings to drop in, but it's better to remove a little material and have a nice press fit bearing sleeve than having a sloppy one.

Just for fun I added an STL for the complete model to use in Simplify3D as your printbed for the preview window.

description.text:
This is a simple wire spool holder for my electronics work area. Hexagonal holes are multi-purpose, lighten the holder, use less plastic when printing, and give somewhere to hang the holder. This is still a work in progress, the nut/bolt needs some work to make it easier to screw and unscrew and I will finish it off with a wire guide/clip.

Update:
There are now mounts that fit in the hex holes with either a hole for a screw or a peg for a pegboard. I printed the peg with support, but as I don't have a pegboard I can't really test this yet.

Update 2:
I've added clips for the sides that allow multiple wire spool holders to be attached together. Insert a clip in to the side of one holder and the complementary clip in to the other side of a second holder and they will slide together. The fit is very tight so either a bit of filing is needed inside the side hexes on the holder or a good sturdy push to get them to fit together. I just pressed them in using the edge of my desk. Once in the holders the fit between the clips is snug, but not too tight, they will hold together well but can be slid apart again afterwards.

This project is to use the least amount of material and hardware to make an incredibly large structure, the components are intended to be scaleable, each node allows for 45 degrees range of motion, the simplest shape you can make is a pyramid, The dome uses tension cables between hexagon nodes to the cable lock to create compression force. This simple design reduces the number of facets and compensates with cables. The inserts are designed to be set into 1/2" PVC, cut to the length required for the intended size and shape, I am using 2 foot segments, but I do not recommend going longer then that. 5mm nuts.

This chess set has been a long running project of mine, I've been waiting to print all of the pieces before uploading it.

Each side of the chess set should have one pawn of each type, see this page for the correct positioning of the different Pawns (or don't).

The Bishops are Elephants, because apparently this was common in medieval versions of chess. Two Bishop files are supplied, one of them has thicker tusks, as I found this made it easier to print in ABS.

There's no overarching theme to the set, other than the consistency that comes from being designed by a single person, using a single tool (Blender)

title: Mac Mini rack mount bracket with remote power switch

description.text:
This mount allows a single Mac Mini (2012 model - check dimensions if yours is different) to be fastened to a 1u 19" equipment rack shelf. It includes a push rod and lever to operate the power switch from the front of the rack (cables to the back). The width allows 2 mac mini's to be mounted side by side in a 1u shelf.

Once printed the push rod needs a little gentle sanding to make it move freely through the holes provided for it. A 3mm nut and bolt attach it to the lever and a small self tapping screw and washer secure the lever to its' stud. The assembly can be held down with 3mm nuts and bolts on the side with the lever (holes provided in the base) and self tapping screws to the other side (use the top bracket as a template to align your holes - same spacing). The 2 top brackets securely hold the mac mini down.
The bracket is designed to not have any elements passing under the mac mini to preserve airflow from front to back.

This project is concern about development of a new Fidget Spinner to help group of people. The team made a research and decided to target a group of child who have MD disease. These children need a toy to keep them continuously play with the spinner to help them moving their hand’s muscles. The team made an experiment using the bearing “608” with the spinner in the lap, the team found that the spinner was spinning approximately 10 second. This experiment shows that the child who uses the Spinner must be hitting the Spinner every 10 second, and this is the main purpose that the team is looking for.
The team made into account that the Spinner has to be attractive by making it color-able, in addition of the other criteria such as safety. The design being created using SolidWorks. sketch, drawing and assembly were made to be ready for printing.

Note: you can change the bearings we have chosen to a bearings you lie so you can have spin for a longer time.

description.text:
This is a simple yet challenging puzzle, the goal is to move all the disks to another peg while still following the rules. The following paragraph is from a website about this puzzle.

The mathematical puzzle Les Tours de Hanoï was invented by the French mathematician Édouard Lucas (1842-1891), and first described in his 1883 publication Récréations Mathématiques. The premise is simple. Three pegs are attached upright to a horizontal board. Several disks of different sizes, with holes drilled through their centers, are stacked on one of the pegs, from smallest at the top to largest at the bottom. The object is to move all of the disks from one peg to another in as few moves as possible. There are three rules: 1) only one disk may be moved at a time; 2) a larger disk may never be placed atop a smaller disk; 3) each move must be complete and non-overlapping, that is, a disk removed from one peg must be moved to another peg before another disk may be moved.

Here is the website for who ever is interested:
http://www.signalsandnoises.com/Works/TowersTechnical.htm

Enjoy!

The tower of hanoi puzzle The mathematical puzzle Les Tours de Hanoï was invented by the French mathematician Édouard Lucas (1842-1891), and first described in his 1883 publication Récréations Mathématiques. Several disks of different sizes, with holes drilled through their centers, are stacked on one of the pegs, from smallest at the top to largest at the bottom. The object is to move all of the disks from one peg to another in as few moves as possible. There are three rules: 1) only one disk may be moved at a time; 2) a larger disk may never be placed atop a smaller disk; 3) each move must be complete and non-overlapping, that is, a disk removed from one peg must be moved to another peg before another disk may be moved.

title: FPV AIO mount for Syma X5C

description.text:
This is an FPV AIO camera mount for a Syma X5C. It is meant to be strapped on top of the canopy. I use this mount on my brushless Syma X5C to fly FPV with it. The mount has a hole for the battery strap to slip through for secure mounting.

The mount was designed with this Lantian AIO unit in mind, but I also used it successfully with a TX01 module.

UPDATE 08/20/2017: Added a revised mount with an additional slot to hold a DC/DC converter for AIO systems that require 5V such as the Boldclash F08.

Print the mount in TPU, I personally use Ninjaflex. Using a flexible material is advisable because you need to be able to pull the frontside with the lens hole forward to insert the module. You can then secure the module in place using some elastic bands.
If you use a hard plastic such as PLA then you are advised to cut away some plastic to modify the hole into a slot. Again you can then secure the module with elastic bands.

This mount is quite heavy so if you mount it on an original X5C it might fly a bit sluggish... I use it exclusively on my brushless 3S X5C.

i wanted to add a BLTouch to my printer just to learn the firmware settings and so on. so i whiped up this quick mount that replaces that fan in the rear with a BLTouch. there are also shims for all those various hotend setups people are running.

probably the best part about this mount is how close it gets to the hot end, it is centered behind the nozzle so you only have a Y offset of roughly 20mm in marlin

EDIT: Photos have been added and i have fully calibrated and ran many test prints using the autobed leveling and this thing works like a dream, the shims are great to swap out and get you in the right ballpark that way you dont have to use huge Z offsets, i dont guess they would hurt much but atleast it doesnt feel like your making large changes ;). i am gonna mark this thing as completed, let me know if you have any questions or requests, im almost positive this will work with any E3D setup you can dream of but i could be wrong.

Testing of a drive method for 3D printer with spectra line.
Grooves in drive pulley are parallel as is the idler roller grooves, the idea is that the angle of line going to the drive will never change no matter where how far its "wound" up.
Normally if just wrap the pulley it will act like a screw and cause the line to climb or lower on the pulley.
I did not get any photos of it but I did also try crossing the wraps between the drive and idler roller to slightly boost the contact area on the drive pulley but gained no reduction in the gradual error.

This failed because no matter the number of turns or line tension I would still have a slow gradual loss of position during printing.

However i'm still posting this as it could still be useful for a camera slide or linear motion system where perfect repeatable position is not needed.

STL files are mostly for reference, idler side had a bolt and a bearing on the top and bottom.

Video of the motion: https://youtu.be/9TBoSpT2unQ

Inspired by this Rob Povey's blog:
http://3dprinterhell.blogspot.com/2013/06/a-better-filament-drive.html?m=1

Also a video by Rikard Hamrin
youtube.com/watch?v=pKerL-opsj4

description.text:
A VR headset designed for 6 in. and up tablets and phones. That simple. Customize the clips for your own mobile device. The Qr code is from the cardboard viewer that I based this off, the VRMID. (It should work. I tested it with my tablet, but let me know if it doesn't)
(NOTE: please check the print instructions that dont appear in your library on thingiverse at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2242876 or the main body might crack apart and/or the corners of the will come out warped (both happened to me the first time I tried to print it))

Notes:

"Main body" print settings:
Raft
Support (Check the support bridges box)
4 walls
35% infill
(must be done in PLA. ABS will warp in print and crack in use.)

Upper, Lower, and Middle lens layer print settings (fist lay them down thought!):
No raft
No supports
4 walls
100% infill
(Preferably in PLA, but if done in abs use the helper disks on each corner to keep then down)

Upper nexus and Lower nexus Clip (for 2013 Nexus 7 whith gummy protecter) print settings:
Raft
No support
4 walls
25% infill

the blank clip is so you can make it fit your devices.

step 1: remove rafts off all parts and carefully remove supports from "Main body".

step 2: sand edges of raft side of clips.

step 3.insert the lenses (25 mm diameter 41 mm focal length. make sure they face the right way) into the middle lens layer and place the 3 lens layers in the order they are labeled into the Main body, lower first, middle second, and top last. (PS: the middle lens layer may need some sanding to accommodate the lens)

step 4. add tape to lower edges of the Main body to protect your screen from scratches.

step 5. apply the desired clip configuration and your done!
